-LaT8dFU_EYmZO7FLYoi.answer: There are 4 students on a team, though teams of 3 can effectively compete.  If you are registering at least 3 students for a school, you must register them as a team. Schools registering at least one team may bring up to 2 alternates per grade level to a Championships event at no additional cost. Alternates take the Mental Math and Individual Tests to compete for individual awards, while practicing the team events with alternates from other schools. There are NO alternates at the Masters contest.

-LaT8dFXTXOVzEQx_XXa.answer:
Individual awards for grades 7 and up are by math class level. Thus, it is important for coaches and student to properly list the current math class for each participating student. Failure to correctly list the current math class can have significant repercussions.
  • PA, Pre-Algebra is for students have yet to take any Algebra class.
  • A1, Algebra I is for students taking their first course in Algebra.
  • GE, Geometry, sometimes called Integrated 2.
  • A2, Algebra 2 or Integrated 3 is often but not always offered after Geometry.
  • PC, Pre-Calculus is also called Math Analysis or Trigonometry.
  • CA, Calculus students.
-LaT8dFXTXOVzEQx_XXa.question: What are the Math levels for HS, 7/8?

-LaT8dFYtZuehlufYu7C.answer: No, there is only one registration per school per grade.  So, teachers and parents NEED to get together and submit ONE registration for the entire school.
-LaT8dFYtZuehlufYu7C.question: Does each team from the school register separately?

-LaT8dFYtZuehlufYu7D.answer: Registration is due 4 weeks ahead of the competition (this is to allow time to print tests, order awards, etc.). Payment is due 2 weeks ahead of the competition, and is non-refundable at that time. Student names (and math levels, if needed) must be entered on the website 2 weeks  before the competition.
-LaT8dFYtZuehlufYu7D.question: What are the deadlines for registering?

-LaT8dFZ9qVb-CwQjjXj.answer: If a team has competed at Math is Cool previously, their scores are compared with scores statewide to place schools into divisions where they can be competitive ( see method). A new school is assigned to a division by the Regional Director based on its size  and whether it is a "magnet"-type school.
-LaT8dFZ9qVb-CwQjjXj.question: How are the divisions selected?

-LaT8dFaftgvkLIruokq.answer: Students should bring their own pencils (at least two). No calculators are permitted, so they can be left at home. Scratch paper will be provided; don’t bring your own scratch paper.
-LaT8dFaftgvkLIruokq.question: What do students need to bring to the contest?

-LaT8dFaftgvkLIruokr.answer: College Bowl is the only event where spectators may be allowed. The first approach is to find the coach and ask them because they will have the room assignment sheet for all students from the school. If necessary, you may go to the scoring area to get that information .
-LaT8dFaftgvkLIruokr.question: How do I know which room my child is in for College Bowl?

-LaT8dFbtH1BkJALqZOR.answer: Correspondence is sent by e-mail to the email address provided during registration. You may request that communications be sent to multiple people by entering multiple email addresses, separated by commas, during registration.
-LaT8dFbtH1BkJALqZOR.question: Why did I not get emails before the competition?

-LaT8dFc1Brv1EdvLr_w.answer: There are no alternates at Masters, but it is a good idea to have one or two students "in the wings" in case someone gets sick or can't attend at the last minute.
-LaT8dFc1Brv1EdvLr_w.question: Are alternates included in registering/competing at Masters competitions?

-LaT8dFdy7tXIX_DcWZ4.answer: Top 2 or 3 schools in each region for each division, plus additional invitees based on highest school score (minus College Bowl).
-LaT8dFdy7tXIX_DcWZ4.question: How are the Masters qualifiers selected?

history.past:
History of Math Is Cool

"Academics Are Cool" began in the spring of 1996 when Gregg Sampson, a mathematics teacher at Lewis & Clark High School (LCHS) in Spokane, Washington organized a mathematics competition for sixth grade students in the Spokane area. He and members of the LCHS Math Team organized the events, wrote the competition items and implemented the competition at LCHS.

  • The following school year (1996/1997), the competition was expanded to grades 4-12 with grade level competitions held on six dates throughout the school year at LCHS. During the same school year, Triscia Hochstatter, a mathematics teacher at Moses Lake High School (MLHS), organized a grade four and five combined "Math is Cool" competition in Moses Lake, adding more grade levels in the following years.
  • Subsequently, "Math is Cool" competitions were held in Seattle beginning with the 1998/1999 school year conducted by Gregg Sampson and Sean Ahern, a University of Washington student and LCHS alumnus. In 2002 Tom Tosch took over as the Seattle Regional Director.
  • Starting with the 2005/2006 school year, Wenatchee began hosting 4-6th grade competitions.
  • In the 2008/2009 school year, the Vancouver region began hosting 4th-12th grade competitionsl.
  • The next year (2010/2011) Tri-Cities began hosting 4-6th grades.
  • In 2015-2016 Coeur d’Alene began hosting 4th and 5th grades, adding 6th grade the next year.
  • In the 2017-2018 school year, the 7/8 Championships contest was held on the same date as the 6th grade Championships contest and both Tri-Cities and Wenatchee added the 7/8 contest.
  • In the year 2000-2001, the approximate number of students that competed was 3686. By the 2016-2017 school year, that number had grown to over 8000.

rules.past:
The Math Is Cool Eligibility Rules

Math Is Cool will follow the MATHCOUNTS school and student eligibility rules. An excerpt from the MATHCOUNTS Handbook appears below.

A school is defined as the educational institution, registered with the state, that graduates or promotes students from one grade to the next. Only schools or organizations that meet this definition may register teams for Math is Cool competitions. Further, only students whose permanent record is at the school for may participate on the school team.

Anyone can register to participate as an Individual.

--- From the MATHCOUNTS Handbook ---

School Definitions: Academic centers or enrichment programs that do not function as students' official school of record are not eligible to register. If it is unclear whether an educational institution is considered a school, please contact your local Department of Education for specific criteria governing your state.

School Enrollment Status: A student may compete only for his or her official school of record. A student's school of record is the student's base or main school. A student taking limited course work at a second school or educational center may not register or compete for that second school or center, even if the student is not competing for his or her school of record. MATHCOUNTS registration is not determined by where a student takes his or her math course. If there is any doubt about a student's school of record, the local or state coordinator must be contacted for a decision before registering.
